\n| years8 = 2017\u20132019 | clubs8 = [[Makedonikos F.C.|Makedonikos]]         | caps8 =    | goals8 = \n| years9 = 2019\u2013     | clubs9 = [[AO Poros F.C.|AO Poros]]               | caps9 =    | goals9 = \n| nationalyears2 =\n| nationalteam2 = \n| nationalcaps2 =    \n| nationalgoals2 =  \n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate =\n}}\n'''\u00c9tienne Le Doux Moussa Pokong''' (born 13 August 1987<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Tunisie Sports|title=Cache of Championat de Tunisie, Ligue 1 2007/2008, Effectif Club Africain (CA)|url=http://google.com/search?q=cache:JNs4x3mgOe8J:www.tn-sports.com/index.php%3Foption%3Dcom_joomleague%26func%3DshowPlayers%26p%3D1%26ttid%3D2%26Itemid%3D67+site:www.tn-sports.com+Pokong&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=24&gl=us|accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref> in [[Garoua]]) is a [[Cameroon]]ian [[football (soccer)|football]] player who plays for [[AO Poros F.C.|AO Poros]].\n\n==Club career==\nPokong transferred to Club Africain in January 2006,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Tunisie-Foot|title=LP 1: Transferts officiels|url=http://www.tunisie-foot.com/ipb/lofiversion/index.php?t64-50.html|accessdate=2008-12-16}}</ref> he cames from [[FS d'Akonolinga]].<ref>[http://www.camfoot.com/article.php3?id_article=6362 D1 : Le Tonnerre s\u2019offre un bon plat de \"Kanga\"]</ref> After three years resign with the Tunisian club [[Club Africain]] to join [[Al-Khor Sports Club]].<ref>[http://footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.moussa-etienne.pokong.40779.en.html Moussa Pokong : Al-Khor - Footballdatabase.eu]</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2019, Pokong joined Greece club [[AO Poros F.C.|AO Poros]].<ref>[https://sportsup.gr/2019/08/20/spoudaio-deal-ston-poro-me-moussa-pokong/ \u03a3\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03b1\u03af\u03bf deal \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 Moussa Pokong!], sportsup.gr, 20 August 2019</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHe earned his first call-up for the [[Cameroon national football team]] on 14 October 2007 for a qualification game against [[Morocco national football team]].<ref>[http://www.camfoot.com/Maroc-Cameroun-Etienne-Le-Doux.html Maroc \u2013 Cameroun : Moussa Pokong remplace Mbia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203162837/http://camfoot.com/Maroc-Cameroun-Etienne-Le-Doux.html |date=2009-02-03 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/www.laget.se/www.texasrangers.com?sport=soccer&page=player&id=53227 Scoresway.com Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pokong, Moussa}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Cameroon international footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Africain players]]\n[[Category:Al-Khor SC players]]\n[[Category:US Monastir players]]\n[[Category:Makedonikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Iraklis Psachna F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Football League (Greece) players]]\n[[Category:Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1 players]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Tunisia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Greece]]\n{{Cameroon-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal Links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moussa_Pokong"}
{"title_page": "The Stendhal Syndrome", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = The Stendhal Syndrome\n| image           = Sindrome di Stendhal.jpg\n| caption         = Italian theatrical release poster\n| director        = [[Dario Argento]]\n| producer        = Dario Argento<BR>[[Giuseppe Colombo]]<br/>Walter Massi\n| screenplay      = Dario Argento\n| story           = Dario Argento<br>[[Franco Ferrini]]\n| based on        = ''La Sindrome di Stendha'' by [[Graziella Magherini]]\n| starring        = [[Asia Argento]]<br>[[Thomas Kretschmann]]<br>[[Marco Leonardi]]\n| music           = [[Ennio Morricone]]\n| cinematography  = [[Giuseppe Rotunno]]\n| editing         = Angelo Nicolini\n| studio          = Cine 2000<br/>Medusa Produzione\n| distributor     = [[Miramax]] (1996 release)<br>[[Troma Entertainment]] (2000 re-release)\n| released        = {{Film date|1996|01|26}}\n| runtime         = 120 minutes\n| country         = Italy\n| language        = Italian\n| budget          = $3,800,000 <small>(estimated)</small>\n| gross           = [[Italian lira|\u20a4]]5,443,000,000 <small>(Italy)</small>\n}}\n\n'''''The Stendhal Syndrome''''' ''(Ital. La Sindrome di Stendhal)'' is a 1996 Italian [[horror film|horror]] film written and directed by [[Dario Argento]] and starring his daughter [[Asia Argento]]. It was the first Italian film to use [[computer-generated imagery]] (CGI).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0117658/trivia |title=The Stendhal Syndrome |work=[[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Stendhal syndrome]] is considered a real syndrome by some, first diagnosed in [[Florence]], Italy in 1982. Argento said he experienced Stendhal syndrome as a child. While touring Athens with his parents young Dario was climbing the steps of the Parthenon when he was overcome by a trance that caused him to become lost from his parents for hours. The experience was so strong that Argento never forgot it; he immediately thought of it when he came across [[Graziella Magherini]]'s book about the syndrome, which would become the basis of the film.\n\nIt was a [[box office]] hit when released in Italy, grossing \u20a45,443,000,000 [[Italian lira]] ([[United States dollar|US]] $3,809,977).\n\n== Plot ==\n\nDetective Anna Manni travels to [[Florence]] on the trail of a [[serial killer]], Alfredo Grossi. While visiting a museum, Anna is overcome by [[Stendhal syndrome]], a condition which causes the sufferer to become overwhelmed when viewing great works of art. When Alfredo learns of Anna's disorder, he uses it to disable her before he kidnaps her and subjects her to a brutal and sadistic sexual attack. Although she manages to escape, Anna is left deeply [[psychological trauma|traumatized]]. Alfredo continues to track her movements and is able to capture her again. This time, however, Anna turns the tables on her abductor, breaking free of his grasp, badly wounding him in the process, and knocking him into a river.\n\nWhile the police, believing Alfredo to be dead, search the river for his body, Anna meets and soon falls in love with Marie, a young French art student. Anna also takes sessions with a psychologist in an effort to come to terms with her own deep-seated emotional trauma. That trauma is intensified when Anna begins to receive phone calls from the supposedly-dead Alfredo. When Marie is found murdered, Anna's psychologist, concerned about her mental state, visits her at home. While he is there, a colleague of Anna's, Marco, calls to notify her that Alfredo's body has in fact been found. This leads to the psychologist realizing the truth, and he confronts Anna with the reality that she herself is Marie's murderer. Marco arrives at Anna's apartment, only to find that she has killed her psychologist as well. As he attempts to take Anna's gun from her, she confesses that Alfredo is now inside her, ordering her to do terrible things, whereupon she murders Marco. The police arrive on the scene and ultimately arrest her after she wanders the streets.\n\n== Cast ==\n\n* [[Asia Argento]] as Det. Anna Manni\n* [[Thomas Kretschmann]] as Alfredo Grossi\n* [[Marco Leonardi]] as Marco Longhi\n* [[Luigi Diberti]] as Insp. Manetti\n* [[Paolo Bonacelli]] as Dr. Cavanna\n* Julien Lambroschini as Marie Beyle\n* John Quentin as Mr. Manni\n* [[Franco Diogene]] as Victim's husband\n* Lucia Stara as the Shop assistant\n* Sonia Topazio as Victim in Florence\n* [[Lorenzo Crespi]] as Giulio\n* Vera Gemma as the Policewoman\n* John Pedeferri as Hydraulic engineer\n* [[Veronica Lazar]] as Mrs. Beyle\n* Mario Diano as the Coroner\n*[[Cinzia Monreale]] as Mrs. Grossi\n* Eleonora Vizzini as Anna Manni (child)\n\n== Production ==\nUpon release, the alternate title was The Strendahl System. Asia Argento, can you verify this?\n\n[[Bridget Fonda]] was originally set to star in the role of Anna, but dropped out before the start of production, and [[Jennifer Jason Leigh]] was considered as a possible replacement before Dario Argento eventually cast his own daughter, Asia, in the role.<ref>Jones, Alan. ''Profondo Argento: The Man, the Myths & the Magic'' (FAB Press, 2004), p. 229. {{ISBN|190325423X}}.</ref> [[Thomas Kretschmann]] was cast as Alfredo Grossi because he had previously worked with Asia on the film ''[[La Reine Margot (1994 film)|La Reine Margot]]'' (1994) and she recommended him to her father.<ref>Jones, Alan. ''Profondo Argento: The Man, the Myths & the Magic''. (FAB Press, 2004), p. 231. {{ISBN|190325423X}}.</ref>\n\nThe opening scene was shot in [[Florence]] at Italy's famed [[Uffizi Gallery]]. Dario Argento is the only director ever granted permission to shoot there.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} \n\nThe work that Anna literally steps into is a painting by [[Rembrandt]], depicting 17th century policemen and titled ''[[The Night Watch (painting)|The Night Watch]]''. The painting that causes Anna to faint in the museum is ''[[Landscape with the Fall of Icarus]]'', by [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder|Bruegel]].\n\nThe footage of Anna underwater after she faints in the gallery was shot in the sea.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The huge grouper fish that Anna kisses was a remote model that was being pulled through the water by cables attached to a small float on the ocean's surface.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} Mere moments after wrapping the underwater shoot, the fish stopped working.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nThis would be the last fiction feature film for acclaimed director of photography [[Giuseppe Rotunno]]. The following year he shot a documentary on [[Marcello Mastroianni]] before retiring.\n\nGraffiti artists were brought in to cover the walls of Alfredo's underground lair with graffiti. In one night the group created over one hundred square feet of graffiti-covered walls at the location.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nThis is the second of (to date) five films in which Argento has directed his daughter, Asia, the four others being: ''[[Trauma (1993 film)|Trauma]]'', ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1998 film)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', ''[[The Mother of Tears]]'' and ''[[Dracula 3D]]''. She also had roles in ''[[Demons 2]]'' and ''[[The Church (1989 film)|The Church]]'', both of which her father produced.\n\nArgento planned on making a sequel to ''The Stendhal Syndrome'' which would follow detective Anna Manni on another case. However, Asia was unavailable so the character's name was changed (to Anna Mari) and [[Stefania Rocca]] was cast. The resulting film is 2004's ''[[The Card Player]]''.\n\n== Release ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n\nThe film carries a 77% 'Fresh' rating from [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 13 reviews<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/stendhal_syndrome/ |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> indicating positive reviews, and was nominated for a [[Saturn Award]] for Best Home Video Release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0117658/awards?ref_=tt_awd |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Awards |accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nResponse from critics was mixed, with ''[[AllRovi|AllMovie]]''{{'}}s Jason Buchanan calling the film \"a sadistic and disturbing psychological exploration\", but one that is \"ultimately a victim of its own excess and the director's tendency to overcomplicate a fairly simple storyline.\" Buchanan praised the film's \"stunningly visual opening sequence\" and [[Ennio Morricone]]'s \"hauntingly hypnotic score\" but criticized how \"the seemingly meandering plot grinds to a halt just as it should truly shine.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-stendhal-syndrome-v135853/review |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Review - AllMovie |last=Buchanan |first=Jason |work=[[AllRovi|AllMovie]] |accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s David Rooney gave the film a mixed review, praising the film's \"exhilarating\" opening sequence and Giuseppe Rotunno's \"cool and elegant\" cinematography, but lamented that \"[a]s with much of the director\u2019s work, large sections of plot are pure hokum, and the gradual slackening of both pace and suspense in a sluggish second half only underlines the increasing silliness.\"<ref name=Rooney>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/the-stendhal-syndrome-1200445110/ |title=Review: 'The Stendhal Syndrome' |accessdate=20 September 2016 |author=Rooney, David |date=4 February 1996 |work=Variety }}</ref>\n\n[[Maitland McDonagh]] gave a mostly positive review, writing that \"this isn't a return to the baroque heights of ''[[Opera (film)|Opera]]'' and ''[[Tenebrae (film)|Tenebrae]]''. But it's a must-see for Argento completists, driven by a brave and disturbing performance by the director's daughter, Asia\", though she criticized the film for taking \"a serious wrong turn around the time Anna buys a blond, femme-fatale wig.\"<ref name=McDonagh>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/movies/the-stendhal-syndrome/review/132133/ |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Review |accessdate=20 September 2016 |author=McDonagh, Maitland |work=TV Guide }}</ref>\n\n=== Home video ===\n\nIn the U.S., ''The Stendhal Syndrome'' is distributed by [[B movie]] company [[Troma Entertainment]]. A new special edition [[DVD]] of the film was released by [[Blue Underground]] on 30 August 2007.\n\nFor its initial release in the United Kingdom, eleven cuts, primarily to the rape scenes, violence and some dialogue, totaling 2 minutes 47 seconds were made by the distributor before submission to the [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]] for a video certificate. The 2005 UK DVD release, by Arrow Pictures, had all previous cuts waived and represents the full-length English version, although like all English releases it omits the two scenes exclusive to the Italian version. Since the uncut version has never been submitted to the British Board of Film Classification, this version was withdrawn and re-released in a cut form.\n\nBlue Underground released ''The Stendahl Syndrome'' on Blu-ray in 2008, which contains the entire film uncut, including the additional Italian-only scenes (still in Italian, with English subtitles). The company re-released the film in 2017 in three-disc limited edition.\n\n== Versions ==\n\n* The US DVD release by Troma is the complete version of the English language edition but, like all English releases, is still missing around two minutes of material exclusive to the Italian print.\n* The Italian release is around two minutes longer than the English export version, including an additional scene where Anna calls the husband of one of Alfredo's victims and another where she meets Marie's mother, played by Veronica Lazar (whose name is included in the credits of all versions, even those in which she does not appear).\n\n==Further reading==\n* Julian Hoxter. \"Anna with the Devil Inside: Klein, Argento and 'The Stendhal Syndrome'\" in Andy Black (ed), ''Necronomicon: The Journal of Horror and Erotic Cinema: Book Two'', London: Creation Books, 1998, pp.&nbsp;99\u2013109.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb title|0117658}}\n\n{{Dario Argento}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stendhal Syndrome, The}}\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:1996 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ennio Morricone]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dario Argento]]\n[[Category:Films set in Florence]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tuscany]]\n[[Category:Giallo films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian thriller films]]\n[[Category:Miramax films]]\n[[Category:Police detective films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Dario Argento]]\n[[Category:Italian serial killer films]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = The Stendhal Syndrome\n| image           = Sindrome di Stendhal.jpg\n| caption         = Italian theatrical release poster\n| director        = [[Dario Argento]]\n| producer        = Dario Argento<BR>[[Giuseppe Colombo]]<br/>Walter Massi\n| screenplay      = Dario Argento\n| story           = Dario Argento<br>[[Franco Ferrini]]\n| based on        = ''La Sindrome di Stendha'' by [[Graziella Magherini]]\n| starring        = [[Asia Argento]]<br>[[Thomas Kretschmann]]<br>[[Marco Leonardi]]\n| music           = [[Ennio Morricone]]\n| cinematography  = [[Giuseppe Rotunno]]\n| editing         = Angelo Nicolini\n| studio          = Cine 2000<br/>Medusa Produzione\n| distributor     = [[Miramax]] (1996 release)<br>[[Troma Entertainment]] (2000 re-release)\n| released        = {{Film date|1996|01|26}}\n| runtime         = 120 minutes\n| country         = Italy\n| language        = Italian\n| budget          = $3,800,000 <small>(estimated)</small>\n| gross           = [[Italian lira|\u20a4]]5,443,000,000 <small>(Italy)</small>\n}}\n\n'''''The Stendhal Syndrome''''' ''(Ital. La Sindrome di Stendhal)'' is a 1996 Italian [[horror film|horror]] film written and directed by [[Dario Argento]] and starring his daughter [[Asia Argento]]. It was the first Italian film to use [[computer-generated imagery]] (CGI).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0117658/trivia |title=The Stendhal Syndrome |work=[[Internet Movie Database]] |accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Stendhal syndrome]] is considered a real syndrome by some, first diagnosed in [[Florence]], Italy in 1982. Argento said he experienced Stendhal syndrome as a child. While touring Athens with his parents young Dario was climbing the steps of the Parthenon when he was overcome by a trance that caused him to become lost from his parents for hours. The experience was so strong that Argento never forgot it; he immediately thought of it when he came across [[Graziella Magherini]]'s book about the syndrome, which would become the basis of the film.\n\nIt was a [[box office]] hit when released in Italy, grossing \u20a45,443,000,000 [[Italian lira]] ([[United States dollar|US]] $3,809,977).\n\n== Plot ==\n\nDetective Anna Manni travels to [[Florence]] on the trail of a [[serial killer]], Alfredo Grossi. While visiting a museum, Anna is overcome by [[Stendhal syndrome]], a condition which causes the sufferer to become overwhelmed when viewing great works of art. When Alfredo learns of Anna's disorder, he uses it to disable her before he kidnaps her and subjects her to a brutal and sadistic sexual attack. Although she manages to escape, Anna is left deeply [[psychological trauma|traumatized]]. Alfredo continues to track her movements and is able to capture her again. This time, however, Anna turns the tables on her abductor, breaking free of his grasp, badly wounding him in the process, and knocking him into a river.\n\nWhile the police, believing Alfredo to be dead, search the river for his body, Anna meets and soon falls in love with Marie, a young French art student. Anna also takes sessions with a psychologist in an effort to come to terms with her own deep-seated emotional trauma. That trauma is intensified when Anna begins to receive phone calls from the supposedly-dead Alfredo. When Marie is found murdered, Anna's psychologist, concerned about her mental state, visits her at home. While he is there, a colleague of Anna's, Marco, calls to notify her that Alfredo's body has in fact been found. This leads to the psychologist realizing the truth, and he confronts Anna with the reality that she herself is Marie's murderer. Marco arrives at Anna's apartment, only to find that she has killed her psychologist as well. As he attempts to take Anna's gun from her, she confesses that Alfredo is now inside her, ordering her to do terrible things, whereupon she murders Marco. The police arrive on the scene and ultimately arrest her after she wanders the streets.\n\n== Cast ==\n\n* [[Asia Argento]] as Det. Anna Manni\n* [[Thomas Kretschmann]] as Alfredo Grossi\n* [[Marco Leonardi]] as Marco Longhi\n* [[Luigi Diberti]] as Insp. Manetti\n* [[Paolo Bonacelli]] as Dr. Cavanna\n* Julien Lambroschini as Marie Beyle\n* John Quentin as Mr. Manni\n* [[Franco Diogene]] as Victim's husband\n* Lucia Stara as the Shop assistant\n* Sonia Topazio as Victim in Florence\n* [[Lorenzo Crespi]] as Giulio\n* Vera Gemma as the Policewoman\n* John Pedeferri as Hydraulic engineer\n* [[Veronica Lazar]] as Mrs. Beyle\n* Mario Diano as the Coroner\n*[[Cinzia Monreale]] as Mrs. Grossi\n* Eleonora Vizzini as Anna Manni (child)\n\n== Production ==\nUpon release, the alternate title was The Strendahl System.\n\n[[Bridget Fonda]] was originally set to star in the role of Anna, but dropped out before the start of production, and [[Jennifer Jason Leigh]] was considered as a possible replacement before Dario Argento eventually cast his own daughter, Asia, in the role.<ref>Jones, Alan. ''Profondo Argento: The Man, the Myths & the Magic'' (FAB Press, 2004), p. 229. {{ISBN|190325423X}}.</ref> [[Thomas Kretschmann]] was cast as Alfredo Grossi because he had previously worked with Asia on the film ''[[La Reine Margot (1994 film)|La Reine Margot]]'' (1994) and she recommended him to her father.<ref>Jones, Alan. ''Profondo Argento: The Man, the Myths & the Magic''. (FAB Press, 2004), p. 231. {{ISBN|190325423X}}.</ref>\n\nThe opening scene was shot in [[Florence]] at Italy's famed [[Uffizi Gallery]]. Dario Argento is the only director ever granted permission to shoot there.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} \n\nThe work that Anna literally steps into is a painting by [[Rembrandt]], depicting 17th century policemen and titled ''[[The Night Watch (painting)|The Night Watch]]''. The painting that causes Anna to faint in the museum is ''[[Landscape with the Fall of Icarus]]'', by [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder|Bruegel]].\n\nThe footage of Anna underwater after she faints in the gallery was shot in the sea.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} The huge grouper fish that Anna kisses was a remote model that was being pulled through the water by cables attached to a small float on the ocean's surface.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} Mere moments after wrapping the underwater shoot, the fish stopped working.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nThis would be the last fiction feature film for acclaimed director of photography [[Giuseppe Rotunno]]. The following year he shot a documentary on [[Marcello Mastroianni]] before retiring.\n\nGraffiti artists were brought in to cover the walls of Alfredo's underground lair with graffiti. In one night the group created over one hundred square feet of graffiti-covered walls at the location.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nThis is the second of (to date) five films in which Argento has directed his daughter, Asia, the four others being: ''[[Trauma (1993 film)|Trauma]]'', ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1998 film)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', ''[[The Mother of Tears]]'' and ''[[Dracula 3D]]''. She also had roles in ''[[Demons 2]]'' and ''[[The Church (1989 film)|The Church]]'', both of which her father produced.\n\nArgento planned on making a sequel to ''The Stendhal Syndrome'' which would follow detective Anna Manni on another case. However, Asia was unavailable so the character's name was changed (to Anna Mari) and [[Stefania Rocca]] was cast. The resulting film is 2004's ''[[The Card Player]]''.\n\n== Release ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n\nThe film carries a 77% 'Fresh' rating from [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 13 reviews<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/stendhal_syndrome/ |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> indicating positive reviews, and was nominated for a [[Saturn Award]] for Best Home Video Release.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0117658/awards?ref_=tt_awd |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Awards |accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nResponse from critics was mixed, with ''[[AllRovi|AllMovie]]''{{'}}s Jason Buchanan calling the film \"a sadistic and disturbing psychological exploration\", but one that is \"ultimately a victim of its own excess and the director's tendency to overcomplicate a fairly simple storyline.\" Buchanan praised the film's \"stunningly visual opening sequence\" and [[Ennio Morricone]]'s \"hauntingly hypnotic score\" but criticized how \"the seemingly meandering plot grinds to a halt just as it should truly shine.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-stendhal-syndrome-v135853/review |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Review - AllMovie |last=Buchanan |first=Jason |work=[[AllRovi|AllMovie]] |accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s David Rooney gave the film a mixed review, praising the film's \"exhilarating\" opening sequence and Giuseppe Rotunno's \"cool and elegant\" cinematography, but lamented that \"[a]s with much of the director\u2019s work, large sections of plot are pure hokum, and the gradual slackening of both pace and suspense in a sluggish second half only underlines the increasing silliness.\"<ref name=Rooney>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/the-stendhal-syndrome-1200445110/ |title=Review: 'The Stendhal Syndrome' |accessdate=20 September 2016 |author=Rooney, David |date=4 February 1996 |work=Variety }}</ref>\n\n[[Maitland McDonagh]] gave a mostly positive review, writing that \"this isn't a return to the baroque heights of ''[[Opera (film)|Opera]]'' and ''[[Tenebrae (film)|Tenebrae]]''. But it's a must-see for Argento completists, driven by a brave and disturbing performance by the director's daughter, Asia\", though she criticized the film for taking \"a serious wrong turn around the time Anna buys a blond, femme-fatale wig.\"<ref name=McDonagh>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/movies/the-stendhal-syndrome/review/132133/ |title=The Stendhal Syndrome - Review |accessdate=20 September 2016 |author=McDonagh, Maitland |work=TV Guide }}</ref>\n\n=== Home video ===\n\nIn the U.S., ''The Stendhal Syndrome'' is distributed by [[B movie]] company [[Troma Entertainment]]. A new special edition [[DVD]] of the film was released by [[Blue Underground]] on 30 August 2007.\n\nFor its initial release in the United Kingdom, eleven cuts, primarily to the rape scenes, violence and some dialogue, totaling 2 minutes 47 seconds were made by the distributor before submission to the [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]] for a video certificate. The 2005 UK DVD release, by Arrow Pictures, had all previous cuts waived and represents the full-length English version, although like all English releases it omits the two scenes exclusive to the Italian version. Since the uncut version has never been submitted to the British Board of Film Classification, this version was withdrawn and re-released in a cut form.\n\nBlue Underground released ''The Stendahl Syndrome'' on Blu-ray in 2008, which contains the entire film uncut, including the additional Italian-only scenes (still in Italian, with English subtitles). The company re-released the film in 2017 in three-disc limited edition.\n\n== Versions ==\n\n* The US DVD release by Troma is the complete version of the English language edition but, like all English releases, is still missing around two minutes of material exclusive to the Italian print.\n* The Italian release is around two minutes longer than the English export version, including an additional scene where Anna calls the husband of one of Alfredo's victims and another where she meets Marie's mother, played by Veronica Lazar (whose name is included in the credits of all versions, even those in which she does not appear).\n\n==Further reading==\n* Julian Hoxter. \"Anna with the Devil Inside: Klein, Argento and 'The Stendhal Syndrome'\" in Andy Black (ed), ''Necronomicon: The Journal of Horror and Erotic Cinema: Book Two'', London: Creation Books, 1998, pp.&nbsp;99\u2013109.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb title|0117658}}\n\n{{Dario Argento}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stendhal Syndrome, The}}\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:1996 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ennio Morricone]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dario Argento]]\n[[Category:Films set in Florence]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tuscany]]\n[[Category:Giallo films]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Italian thriller films]]\n[[Category:Miramax films]]\n[[Category:Police detective films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Dario Argento]]\n[[Category:Italian serial killer films]]\n", "name_user": "69.122.219.24", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eProduction)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Stendhal_Syndrome"}
{"title_page": "Michael P. Fay", "text_new": "{{short description|20th-century American caned in Singapore}}\n{{Other people|Michael Fay|Michael Fay (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Michael Fay\n| image            = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt              = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Michael Peter Fay\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1975|05|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = [[United States|American]]\n| residence        = \n| other_names      = \n| occupation       = Casino manager\n| criminal_charge  = Violation of [[Vandalism Act]]\n| criminal_penalty = Six strokes of the cane\n| criminal_status  = Released\n| known_for        = [[Caning in Singapore]]\n| mother           = Randy Chan<ref name=\"reyes\"/>\n| father           = George Fay\n}}\n\n'''Michael Peter Fay''' (born May 30, 1975), better known simply as '''Michael Fay''', is an American citizen who was the subject of international attention in 1994 when he was sentenced to [[Caning in Singapore|six strokes of the cane]] in [[Singapore]] for theft and vandalism at age 18. Fay pleaded guilty; however, he later maintained that he was advised that such a plea would preclude caning and that his confession was false, that he never vandalized any cars, and that the only crime he committed was stealing signs. Although caning is a routine court sentence in Singapore, its use caused controversy in the United States, and Fay's case was believed to be the first caning involving an American citizen.<ref name=\"LAT19940309\">{{cite news |title= Singapore Blasts Back at Clinton in Caning Case |newspaper =Los Angeles Times |date= March 9, 1994 |first= Charles P. |last=Wallace |url= http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#1474}}</ref> The number of cane strokes in Fay's sentence was ultimately reduced from six to four after United States officials requested leniency.\n\n==Early life==\nFay was born in [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]].<ref name=\"reyes\"/> His mother, Randy, divorced his father, George, when he was eight.<ref name=\"reyes\"/> As a child, he was diagnosed with [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder]] which, his lawyer later claimed, did not contribute to Fay committing vandalism in Singapore.<ref name=nyt19940505>{{cite news |title= Responding to Clinton's Plea, Singapore Cuts 6 Lashes to 4 |work= The New York Times |date= May 5, 1994 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/05/news/05iht-cane_0.html |last= Richardson |first= Michael}}</ref>\n \nAlthough Fay mostly lived with his father after the divorce, he later moved to Singapore to live with his mother and stepfather, Marco Chan, and was enrolled in the [[Singapore American School]].<ref name=\"reyes\"/>\n\n==Theft and vandalism in Singapore==\nIn October 1993, ''[[The Straits Times]]'', Singapore's main English-language newspaper, reported that car vandalism in Singapore was on the rise.<ref name=\"tanooiboon19931007\"/> Cars parked at apartment blocks were being damaged with hot tar, paint remover, red spray paint, and hatchets. Taxi drivers complained that their tires were slashed. In the city center, cars were found with deep scratches and dents. One man complained that he had to refinish his car six times in six months.<ref name=\"tanooiboon19931007\"/>\n\nThe [[Singapore Police Force|Singapore police]] eventually arrested 16-year-old Andy Shiu Chi Ho, a Chinese citizen from [[Hong Kong]]. He was not caught vandalizing cars, but was charged with driving his father's car without a license. After questioning Shiu, the police questioned several expatriate students from the [[Singapore American School]], including Fay, and charged them with more than 50 counts of vandalism.<ref name=\"tanooiboon19931007\">Tan Ooi Boon (October 7, 1993). \"9 foreign students held for vandalism\". ''The Straits Times'' (Singapore). p. 1.</ref> Fay pleaded guilty to vandalizing the cars in addition to stealing road signs. He later maintained that he was advised that such a plea would preclude caning and that his confession was false, that he never vandalized any cars, and that the only crime he committed was stealing signs.<ref name=\"NYT19940316\">Philip Shenon (March 16, 1994). [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/16/world/singapore-journal-a-flogging-sentence-brings-a-cry-of-pain-in-us.html \"A Flogging Sentence Brings a Cry of Pain in U.S.\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>\"Cane teen says he's innocent\", ''Daily News'', New York, June 22, 1994.</ref>\n\nUnder the 1966 [[Vandalism Act]], originally passed to curb the spread of political [[graffiti]] and which specifically penalized vandalism of government property,<ref name=\"reyes\">Reyes, Alejandro (May 25, 1994). [http://www.corpun.com/awfay9405.htm \"Rough Justice: A Caning in Singapore Stirs Up a Fierce Debate About Crime And Punishment\"], ''Asiaweek''. Hong Kong.</ref> Fay was sentenced on March 3, 1994 to four months in jail, a fine of 3,500 [[Singapore dollar]]s ([[United States dollar|US$]]2,214 or [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]1,514 at the time), and six [[Caning in Singapore|strokes of the cane]].<ref>Charles P. Wallace, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#4910 \"Ohio Youth to be Flogged in Singapore\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', March 4, 1994.</ref> Shiu, who pleaded not guilty, was sentenced to eight months in prison and 12 strokes of the cane.<ref>Ian Stewart, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#3891 \"Flogging for vandal\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm |date=September 20, 2010 }}, ''South China Morning Post'' (Hong Kong), April 22, 1994.</ref>\n\nFay's lawyers appealed, arguing that the Vandalism Act provided caning only for [[Wiktionary:indelible#Adjective|indelible]] forms of graffiti vandalism, and that the damaged cars had been cheaply restored to their original condition.<ref>Elena Chong, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9404.htm \"Fay loses appeal\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm |date=September 20, 2010 }}, ''The Straits Times'', Singapore, April 1, 1994</ref>\n\n==Response==\n===From the United States government===\nThe official position of the United States government was that although it recognized Singapore's right to punish Fay within the [[due process]] of law, the punishment of caning was excessive for a teenager who committed a non-violent crime. The United States Embassy in Singapore pointed out that the graffiti damage to the cars was not permanent, but caning would leave Fay with permanent physical scars.<ref name=\"reyes\"/>\n\n[[Bill Clinton]], the [[President of the United States]], called Fay's punishment extreme and mistaken, and pressured the Singapore government to grant Fay clemency from caning. Two dozen United States senators signed a letter to the Singapore government also appealing for clemency.<ref name=nyt19940505/> The Singapore government pointed out that Singaporeans who break the law faced the same punishments as Fay,<ref name=\"LAT19940309\"/> and claimed that Singapore's laws had kept the city free of vandalism and violence of the kind seen in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Karen Fawcett |url= http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#1199 |title=Americans in Singapore condemn caning for teen |work =USA Today |location =Washington D.C. |date =March 9, 1994}}</ref> \n\nNevertheless, [[Ong Teng Cheong]], the then [[President of Singapore|head of state of Singapore]], commuted Fay's caning from six to four strokes as a gesture of respect toward President Clinton.<ref>William Branigin, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9405.htm#3693 \"Singapore Reduces American's Sentence\"], ''The Washington Post'', May 5, 1994.</ref><ref name=nyt19940505/> Shiu's sentence was later also reduced, from 12 strokes to six, after a similar clemency appeal. Fay was caned on May 5, 1994, at Queenstown Remand Centre.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1994-06-22/news/mn-7134_1_michael-fay Singapore Frees Flogged U.S. Teen-Ager : Asia: Michael Fay is 'happy to be out' after early release. He leaves the country, heads for home.], ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', June 22, 1994</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/06/world/singapore-carries-out-the-caning-of-a-us-teen-ager.html \"Singapore Carries Out Caning of U.S. Teenager\"], Philip Shenon, ''The New York Times'', May 6, 1994</ref>\n\n===Public reaction===\nFollowing Fay's sentence, the case received wide coverage by the American and international media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore Hosts Some Most Unruly Guests |work=American Journalism Review |date=August 1994 |url=http://ajr.org/article.asp?id=2093 |author=Rocco Parascandola |access-date=February 24, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014537/http://ajr.org/article.asp?id=2093 |archive-date=September 30, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' ran editorials and op-eds condemning the punishment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#6392 |title=What US columnists say about Fay's caning |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=April 8, 1994 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#6392 |archivedate=September 20, 2010 |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' reported that caning involved \"bits of flesh fly[ing] with each stroke.\"<ref name=\"Don't copy Singapore\">E.g. [https://www.corpun.com/usju9404.htm#02 \"Don't copy Singapore\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208212700/http://www.corpun.com/usju9404.htm |date=February 8, 2009 }}, ''USA Today'', Washington, D.C., April 5, 1994.</ref> The punishment had to be accomplished by trained warders holding high grades in [[martial arts]].<ref>P.M. Raman, [https://www.corpun.com/sgju7409.htm#graphic \"Branding the Bad Hats for Life\"], ''The Straits Times'', Singapore, September 13, 1974.</ref> Public opinion in the USA was mixed. A survey of 23,000 people conducted by National Polling Network found that 53% \"favor whipping and other harsh sentences as an acceptable deterrent to crime in the USA\".<ref>Andrea Stone, [https://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#andrea \"Whipping penalty judged too harsh \u2013 by some\"], ''USA Today'', Washington, March 10, 1994.</ref><ref>Mike Royko, [https://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#royko \"Readers get 'behind' flogging of vandal\"], ''Daily News'', New York, March 30, 1994.</ref><ref name=\"Usborne\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/joe-public-backs-caning-of-american-1367479.html \"'Joe Public' backs caning of American\"], David Usborne, ''[[The Independent]]'', London, April 2, 1994</ref>\n\n==Caning==\nDescribing the caning day, Fay told [[Reuters]] he did not know the time had come for punishment when he was taken from his cell. He said he was bent over a trestle so his buttocks stuck out, with his hands and feet buckled to the structure. He was naked except for a protective rubber pad fixed to his back. The flogger, a doctor, and prison officials were also present. \n\nFay told Reuters the caner walked sharply forward three steps to build power. \"They go 'Count one'\u2014you hear them yell it really loud\u2014and a few seconds later they come, I guess I would call it charging at you with a rattan cane.\" He noted that a prison officer guided him through the ordeal saying: \"OK Michael, three left; OK Michael, two left; OK one more, you're almost done.\" Fay reported that when the fourth stroke was delivered he was immediately unbuckled from the trestle and taken to a cell to recover. The caning, which Fay estimated took one minute, left a \"few streaks of blood\" running down his buttocks, and seven weeks later, left three dark-brown scar patches on his right buttock and four lines each about half-an-inch wide on his left buttock. He said that the wounds hurt for about five days after which they itched as they healed. \"The first couple of days it was very hard to sit,\" Fay reported, but he said he was able to walk after the caning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://buffalonews.com/1994/06/26/teen-tells-of-scars-in-singapore-caning-fay-says-flogging-lasted-about-a-minute/ |title=Teen tells of scars in Singapore caning: Fay says Flogging Lasted about a minute |last=Arkus |first=Michael |date=June 25, 1994 |website=The Buffalo News |access-date=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nAfter his release from prison in June 1994, Fay returned to the United States to live with his biological father.<ref>[http://www.corpun.com/sgju9406.htm#4308 \"The Road From Singapore\"], ''Daily News'', New York, June 22, 1994.</ref> He gave several television interviews, including one with his American lawyer on [[CNN]] with [[Larry King]] on June 29, 1994, in which he admitted taking road signs but denied vandalizing cars.<ref>[http://www.corpun.com/sgju9406.htm#4344 \"Larry King Live\"], ''CNN'', June 29, 1994.</ref> He also claimed that he was ill-treated during questioning, but had shaken hands with the caning operative after his four strokes had been administered.\n\nSeveral months after returning to the United States, Fay suffered burns to his hands and face after a [[butane]] incident.<ref name=\"people\">\"Michael Fay,\" ''People Magazine,'' December 26, 1994, p.60.</ref><ref>\"Drug Rehab For Teen Caned in Singapore,\" ''Chicago Tribune,'' September 29, 1994, p.14.</ref><ref>\"The Nation,\" ''USA Today'', Washington, D.C., September 29, 1994, p.03A.</ref> He was subsequently admitted to the [[Hazelden Betty Ford Foundation|Hazelden]] rehabilitation program for [[Inhalant|butane abuse]].<ref name=\"people\"/> He claimed that sniffing butane \"made [him] forget what happened in Singapore.\"<ref>\"Teen Punished in Singapore Has Drug Habit \u2013 Michael Fay Was Sniffing Butane,\" ''Times-Picayune'', New Orleans, September 29, 1994, p.A24.</ref> In 1996, he was cited in [[Florida]] for a number of violations, including careless driving, reckless driving, not reporting a crash, and having an open bottle of alcohol in a car.<ref>\"Q&A,\" ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,'' October 13, 2003, p.B2.</ref> Later, in 1998, still in Florida, Fay was arrested for possession of [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] and [[drug paraphernalia]], charges to which he confessed but was acquitted<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/1998/0409/040998.feat.feat.2.html Boy Caned in Singapore Makes News Again],\" ''Christian Science Monitor,'' Boston, April 9, 1998, p.18.</ref> because of technical errors in his arrest.<ref>\"Drug Charges Dropped,\" ''Asiaweek,'' Hong Kong, June 29, 1998, p.1.</ref>\n\nDuring an interview with [[China Central Television|CCTV]] in June 2004, [[Lee Kuan Yew]], then [[Senior Minister]] of Singapore, said that Fay hit his father upon his return in the United States, which was suppressed by the American media.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conversation with LKY (CCTV) Part 1/2 (June 2004)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=evs9Qxwwhhw|website=Youtube|accessdate=March 10, 2017|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref> In June 2010, Fay's case was recalled in international news, after another foreigner in Singapore, Swiss IT consultant [[Oliver Fricker]], was sentenced to five months in jail and three strokes of the cane for vandalizing a train.<ref>{{cite news |title= Graffiti man faces Singapore caning |work=BBC News |date=June 25, 2010 |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/asia_pacific/10417167.stm}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported by a Singaporean news outlet in August 2018 that Fay was working as a casino manager in [[Cincinnati]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url= https://mustsharenews.com/michael-fay-today|title= Michael Fay Today |last= Venkat |first= Naveen |date= August 2, 2018 |website= Must Share News \n |publisher= MS News |access-date= February 23, 2019 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n[[Saturday Night Live_(season 19)|Season 19]], episode 18 of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' cold-opened with a sketch of Michael Fay's caning. Host [[Emilio Estevez]] as Fay, [[Kevin Nealon]] administering the caning, [[Rob Schneider]] as the warden, and [[Phil Hartman]] as the doctor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snltranscripts.jt.org/93/93rfay.phtml |title=SNL Transcripts \u2013 Michael Fay Caning |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=April 16, 1994 |website=snltranscripts.jt.org |access-date=March 30, 2018 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/video/singapore-cold-open/2868162?snl=1 |title=Caning in Singapore Cold Open |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=May 25, 2015 |website=NBC.com |publisher=NBCUniversal |access-date=March 30, 2018 |quote=\"Mr. Fay. I have some good news, and bad news.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1994 [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] released a song, \"[[Headline News (song)|Headline News]]\", which satirized the Fay case along with the [[Tonya Harding]] and [[John and Lorena Bobbitt|Bobbitts]] stories.<ref>{{cite interview | last           = Yankovic | first          = Alfred M. | interviewer    = Chad Mitchell | title        = WONC 89.1 FM | date = November 14, 1994 | accessdate     = May 1, 2013 | url     = http://www.al-oholicsanonymous.com/interviews/wonc.txt }}</ref>\n\n\"Headwriter\", a 1994 episode of ''[[The Larry Sanders Show]]'' opened with Sanders making a joke about Fay in the character's opening monologue: \"Michael Fay is back in the U.S. from Singapore. And I can assure you, that is a long flight, especially when you have to stand the whole way.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.springfieldspringfield.co.uk/view_episode_scripts.php?tv-show=the-larry-sanders-show-1992&episode=s03e09|title=The Larry Sanders Show (1992) s03e09 Episode Script &#124; SS|website=Springfield! Springfield!}}</ref>\n\n[[Dr. Dre]] and [[Ice Cube]] referenced the caning in their 1994 single, \"[[Natural Born Killaz]]\".<ref>https://genius.com/Dr-dre-and-ice-cube-natural-born-killaz-lyrics Natural Born Killaz lyrics</ref>\n\nThe case inspired a 1995 ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode, \"[[Bart vs. Australia]]\", in which [[Australia]] is to punish Bart via \"booting\"\u2014a kick in the buttocks using a giant boot (later reduced to a shoe).<ref name=Mirkin>{{cite video |people=Mirkin, David |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 6 DVD commentary for the episode \"Bart vs. Australia\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Amos Yee]]\n*[[Judicial corporal punishment]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Latif, Asad (1994). ''The Flogging of Singapore: The Michael Fay Affair''. Singapore: Times Books International. {{ISBN|981-204-530-9}}\n*[[Gopal Baratham|Baratham, Gopal]] (1994). ''The Caning of Michael Fay''. Singapore: KRP Publication. {{ISBN|981-00-5747-4}}\n*Reyes, Alejandro (May 25, 1994). [http://www.corpun.com/awfay9405.htm Rough Justice: A Caning in Singapore Stirs Up a Fierce Debate About Crime And Punishment], ''Asiaweek'', Hong Kong.\n*The Asiaweek Newsmap (April 27, 1994). ''Asiaweek''.\n*Chew, Valerie (August 5, 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20090825175717/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1554_2009-08-06.html \"Michael Fay\"], ''Singapore Infopedia''. National Library Board.\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#regrettable#regrettable The Singapore Government's response to the American Embassy's statement], April 1, 1994\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fay, Michael P.}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Caning in Singapore]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:People with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|20th-century American caned in Singapore}}\n{{Other people|Michael Fay|Michael Fay (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Michael Fay\n| image            = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt              = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Michael Peter Fay\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1975|05|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = [[United States|American]]\n| residence        = \n| other_names      = \n| occupation       = Casino manager\n| criminal_charge  = Violation of [[Vandalism Act]]\n| criminal_penalty = Six strokes of the cane\n| criminal_status  = Released\n| known_for        = [[Caning in Singapore]]\n| mother           = Randy Chan<ref name=\"reyes\"/>\n| father           = George Fay\n}}\n\n'''Michael Peter Fay''' (born May 30, 1975), better known simply as '''Michael Fay''', is an American citizen who was the subject of international attention in 1994 when he was sentenced to [[Caning in Singapore|six strokes of the cane]] in [[Singapore]] for theft and vandalism at age 18. Fay pleaded guilty; however, he later maintained that he was advised that such a plea would preclude caning and that his confession was false, that he never vandalized any cars, and that the only crime he committed was stealing signs. Although caning is a routine court sentence in Singapore, its use caused controversy in the United States, and Fay's case was believed to be the first caning involving an American citizen.<ref name=\"LAT19940309\">{{cite news |title= Singapore Blasts Back at Clinton in Caning Case |newspaper =Los Angeles Times |date= March 9, 1994 |first= Charles P. |last=Wallace |url= http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#1474}}</ref> The number of cane strokes in Fay's sentence was ultimately reduced from six to four after United States officials requested leniency.\n\n==Early life==\nFay was born in [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]].<ref name=\"reyes\"/> His mother, Randy, divorced his father, George, when he was eight.<ref name=\"reyes\"/> As a child, he was diagnosed with [[Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder]] which, his lawyer later claimed, did not contribute to Fay committing vandalism in Singapore.<ref name=nyt19940505>{{cite news |title= Responding to Clinton's Plea, Singapore Cuts 6 Lashes to 4 |work= The New York Times |date= May 5, 1994 |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/05/news/05iht-cane_0.html |last= Richardson |first= Michael}}</ref>\n \nAlthough Fay mostly lived with his father after the divorce, he later moved to Singapore to live with his mother and stepfather, Marco Chan, and was enrolled in the [[Singapore American School]].<ref name=\"reyes\"/>\n\n==Theft and vandalism in Singapore==\nIn October 1993, ''[[The Straits Times]]'', Singapore's main English-language newspaper, reported that car vandalism in Singapore was on the rise.<ref name=\"tanooiboon19931007\"/> Cars parked at apartment blocks were being damaged with hot tar, paint remover, red spray paint, and hatchets. Taxi drivers complained that their tires were slashed. In the city center, cars were found with deep scratches and dents. One man complained that he had to refinish his car six times in six months.<ref name=\"tanooiboon19931007\"/>\n\nThe [[Singapore Police Force|Singapore police]] eventually arrested 16-year-old Andy Shiu Chi Ho, a Chinese citizen from [[Hong Kong]]. He was not caught vandalizing cars, but was charged with driving his father's car without a license. After questioning Shiu, the police questioned several expatriate students from the [[Singapore American School]], including Fay, and charged them with more than 50 counts of vandalism.<ref name=\"tanooiboon19931007\">Tan Ooi Boon (October 7, 1993). \"9 foreign students held for vandalism\". ''The Straits Times'' (Singapore). p. 1.</ref> Fay pleaded guilty to vandalizing the cars in addition to stealing road signs. He later maintained that he was advised that such a plea would preclude caning and that his confession was false, that he never vandalized any cars, and that the only crime he committed was stealing signs.<ref name=\"NYT19940316\">Philip Shenon (March 16, 1994). [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/16/world/singapore-journal-a-flogging-sentence-brings-a-cry-of-pain-in-us.html \"A Flogging Sentence Brings a Cry of Pain in U.S.\"]. ''The New York Times''.</ref><ref>\"Cane teen says he's innocent\", ''Daily News'', New York, June 22, 1994.</ref>\n\nUnder the 1966 [[Vandalism Act]], originally passed to curb the spread of political [[graffiti]] and which specifically penalized vandalism of government property,<ref name=\"reyes\">Reyes, Alejandro (May 25, 1994). [http://www.corpun.com/awfay9405.htm \"Rough Justice: A Caning in Singapore Stirs Up a Fierce Debate About Crime And Punishment\"], ''Asiaweek''. Hong Kong.</ref> Fay was sentenced on March 3, 1994 to four months in jail, a fine of 3,500 [[Singapore dollar]]s ([[United States dollar|US$]]2,214 or [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]1,514 at the time), and six [[Caning in Singapore|strokes of the cane]].<ref>Charles P. Wallace, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#4910 \"Ohio Youth to be Flogged in Singapore\"], ''Los Angeles Times'', March 4, 1994.</ref> Shiu, who pleaded not guilty, was sentenced to eight months in prison and 12 strokes of the cane.<ref>Ian Stewart, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#3891 \"Flogging for vandal\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm |date=September 20, 2010 }}, ''South China Morning Post'' (Hong Kong), April 22, 1994.</ref>\n\nFay's lawyers appealed, arguing that the Vandalism Act provided caning only for [[Wiktionary:indelible#Adjective|indelible]] forms of graffiti vandalism, and that the damaged cars had been cheaply restored to their original condition.<ref>Elena Chong, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9404.htm \"Fay loses appeal\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm |date=September 20, 2010 }}, ''The Straits Times'', Singapore, April 1, 1994</ref>\n\n==Response==\n===From the United States government===\nThe official position of the United States government was that although it recognized Singapore's right to punish Fay within the [[due process]] of law, the punishment of caning was excessive for a teenager who committed a non-violent crime. The United States Embassy in Singapore pointed out that the graffiti damage to the cars was not permanent, but caning would leave Fay with permanent physical scars.<ref name=\"reyes\"/>\n\n[[Bill Clinton]], the [[President of the United States]], called Fay's punishment extreme and mistaken, and pressured the Singapore government to grant Fay clemency from caning. Two dozen United States senators signed a letter to the Singapore government also appealing for clemency.<ref name=nyt19940505/> The Singapore government pointed out that Singaporeans who break the law faced the same punishments as Fay,<ref name=\"LAT19940309\"/> and claimed that Singapore's laws had kept the city free of vandalism and violence of the kind seen in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Karen Fawcett |url= http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#1199 |title=Americans in Singapore condemn caning for teen |work =USA Today |location =Washington D.C. |date =March 9, 1994}}</ref> \n\nNevertheless, [[Ong Teng Cheong]], the then [[President of Singapore|head of state of Singapore]], commuted Fay's caning from six to four strokes as a gesture of respect toward President Clinton.<ref>William Branigin, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9405.htm#3693 \"Singapore Reduces American's Sentence\"], ''The Washington Post'', May 5, 1994.</ref><ref name=nyt19940505/> Shiu's sentence was later also reduced, from 12 strokes to six, after a similar clemency appeal. Fay was caned on May 5, 1994, at Queenstown Remand Centre.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1994-06-22/news/mn-7134_1_michael-fay Singapore Frees Flogged U.S. Teen-Ager : Asia: Michael Fay is 'happy to be out' after early release. He leaves the country, heads for home.], ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'', June 22, 1994</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/05/06/world/singapore-carries-out-the-caning-of-a-us-teen-ager.html \"Singapore Carries Out Caning of U.S. Teenager\"], Philip Shenon, ''The New York Times'', May 6, 1994</ref>\n\n===Public reaction===\nFollowing Fay's sentence, the case received wide coverage by the American and international media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore Hosts Some Most Unruly Guests |work=American Journalism Review |date=August 1994 |url=http://ajr.org/article.asp?id=2093 |author=Rocco Parascandola |access-date=February 24, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014537/http://ajr.org/article.asp?id=2093 |archive-date=September 30, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' ran editorials and op-eds condemning the punishment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#6392 |title=What US columnists say about Fay's caning |newspaper=The Straits Times |location=Singapore |date=April 8, 1994 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#6392 |archivedate=September 20, 2010 |access-date=August 13, 2019 }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' reported that caning involved \"bits of flesh fly[ing] with each stroke.\"<ref name=\"Don't copy Singapore\">E.g. [http://www.corpun.com/usju9404.htm#02 \"Don't copy Singapore\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208212700/http://www.corpun.com/usju9404.htm |date=February 8, 2009 }}, ''USA Today'', Washington, D.C., April 5, 1994.</ref> The punishment had to be accomplished by trained warders holding high grades in [[martial arts]].<ref>P.M. Raman, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju7409.htm#graphic \"Branding the Bad Hats for Life\"], ''The Straits Times'', Singapore, September 13, 1974.</ref> Public opinion in the USA was mixed. A survey of 23,000 people conducted by National Polling Network found that 53% \"favor whipping and other harsh sentences as an acceptable deterrent to crime in the USA\".<ref>Andrea Stone, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#andrea \"Whipping penalty judged too harsh \u2013 by some\"], ''USA Today'', Washington, March 10, 1994.</ref><ref>Mike Royko, [http://www.corpun.com/sgju9403.htm#royko \"Readers get 'behind' flogging of vandal\"], ''Daily News'', New York, March 30, 1994.</ref><ref name=\"Usborne\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/joe-public-backs-caning-of-american-1367479.html \"'Joe Public' backs caning of American\"], David Usborne, ''[[The Independent]]'', London, April 2, 1994</ref>\n\n==Caning==\nDescribing the caning day, Fay told [[Reuters]] he did not know the time had come for punishment when he was taken from his cell. He said he was bent over a trestle so his buttocks stuck out, with his hands and feet buckled to the structure. He was naked except for a protective rubber pad fixed to his back. The flogger, a doctor, and prison officials were also present. \n\nFay told Reuters the caner walked sharply forward three steps to build power. \"They go 'Count one'\u2014you hear them yell it really loud\u2014and a few seconds later they come, I guess I would call it charging at you with a rattan cane.\" He noted that a prison officer guided him through the ordeal saying: \"OK Michael, three left; OK Michael, two left; OK one more, you're almost done.\" Fay reported that when the fourth stroke was delivered he was immediately unbuckled from the trestle and taken to a cell to recover. The caning, which Fay estimated took one minute, left a \"few streaks of blood\" running down his buttocks, and seven weeks later, left three dark-brown scar patches on his right buttock and four lines each about half-an-inch wide on his left buttock. He said that the wounds hurt for about five days after which they itched as they healed. \"The first couple of days it was very hard to sit,\" Fay reported, but he said he was able to walk after the caning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://buffalonews.com/1994/06/26/teen-tells-of-scars-in-singapore-caning-fay-says-flogging-lasted-about-a-minute/ |title=Teen tells of scars in Singapore caning: Fay says Flogging Lasted about a minute |last=Arkus |first=Michael |date=June 25, 1994 |website=The Buffalo News |access-date=February 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nAfter his release from prison in June 1994, Fay returned to the United States to live with his biological father.<ref>[http://www.corpun.com/sgju9406.htm#4308 \"The Road From Singapore\"], ''Daily News'', New York, June 22, 1994.</ref> He gave several television interviews, including one with his American lawyer on [[CNN]] with [[Larry King]] on June 29, 1994, in which he admitted taking road signs but denied vandalizing cars.<ref>[http://www.corpun.com/sgju9406.htm#4344 \"Larry King Live\"], ''CNN'', June 29, 1994.</ref> He also claimed that he was ill-treated during questioning, but had shaken hands with the caning operative after his four strokes had been administered.\n\nSeveral months after returning to the United States, Fay suffered burns to his hands and face after a [[butane]] incident.<ref name=\"people\">\"Michael Fay,\" ''People Magazine,'' December 26, 1994, p.60.</ref><ref>\"Drug Rehab For Teen Caned in Singapore,\" ''Chicago Tribune,'' September 29, 1994, p.14.</ref><ref>\"The Nation,\" ''USA Today'', Washington, D.C., September 29, 1994, p.03A.</ref> He was subsequently admitted to the [[Hazelden Betty Ford Foundation|Hazelden]] rehabilitation program for [[Inhalant|butane abuse]].<ref name=\"people\"/> He claimed that sniffing butane \"made [him] forget what happened in Singapore.\"<ref>\"Teen Punished in Singapore Has Drug Habit \u2013 Michael Fay Was Sniffing Butane,\" ''Times-Picayune'', New Orleans, September 29, 1994, p.A24.</ref> In 1996, he was cited in [[Florida]] for a number of violations, including careless driving, reckless driving, not reporting a crash, and having an open bottle of alcohol in a car.<ref>\"Q&A,\" ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,'' October 13, 2003, p.B2.</ref> Later, in 1998, still in Florida, Fay was arrested for possession of [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] and [[drug paraphernalia]], charges to which he confessed but was acquitted<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/1998/0409/040998.feat.feat.2.html Boy Caned in Singapore Makes News Again],\" ''Christian Science Monitor,'' Boston, April 9, 1998, p.18.</ref> because of technical errors in his arrest.<ref>\"Drug Charges Dropped,\" ''Asiaweek,'' Hong Kong, June 29, 1998, p.1.</ref>\n\nDuring an interview with [[China Central Television|CCTV]] in June 2004, [[Lee Kuan Yew]], then [[Senior Minister]] of Singapore, said that Fay hit his father upon his return in the United States, which was suppressed by the American media.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conversation with LKY (CCTV) Part 1/2 (June 2004)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=evs9Qxwwhhw|website=Youtube|accessdate=March 10, 2017|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref> In June 2010, Fay's case was recalled in international news, after another foreigner in Singapore, Swiss IT consultant [[Oliver Fricker]], was sentenced to five months in jail and three strokes of the cane for vandalizing a train.<ref>{{cite news |title= Graffiti man faces Singapore caning |work=BBC News |date=June 25, 2010 |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/asia_pacific/10417167.stm}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported by a Singaporean news outlet in August 2018 that Fay was working as a casino manager in [[Cincinnati]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url= https://mustsharenews.com/michael-fay-today|title= Michael Fay Today |last= Venkat |first= Naveen |date= August 2, 2018 |website= Must Share News \n |publisher= MS News |access-date= February 23, 2019 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n[[Saturday Night Live_(season 19)|Season 19]], episode 18 of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' cold-opened with a sketch of Michael Fay's caning. Host [[Emilio Estevez]] as Fay, [[Kevin Nealon]] administering the caning, [[Rob Schneider]] as the warden, and [[Phil Hartman]] as the doctor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snltranscripts.jt.org/93/93rfay.phtml |title=SNL Transcripts \u2013 Michael Fay Caning |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=April 16, 1994 |website=snltranscripts.jt.org |access-date=March 30, 2018 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/video/singapore-cold-open/2868162?snl=1 |title=Caning in Singapore Cold Open |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=May 25, 2015 |website=NBC.com |publisher=NBCUniversal |access-date=March 30, 2018 |quote=\"Mr. Fay. I have some good news, and bad news.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1994 [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]] released a song, \"[[Headline News (song)|Headline News]]\", which satirized the Fay case along with the [[Tonya Harding]] and [[John and Lorena Bobbitt|Bobbitts]] stories.<ref>{{cite interview | last           = Yankovic | first          = Alfred M. | interviewer    = Chad Mitchell | title        = WONC 89.1 FM | date = November 14, 1994 | accessdate     = May 1, 2013 | url     = http://www.al-oholicsanonymous.com/interviews/wonc.txt }}</ref>\n\n\"Headwriter\", a 1994 episode of ''[[The Larry Sanders Show]]'' opened with Sanders making a joke about Fay in the character's opening monologue: \"Michael Fay is back in the U.S. from Singapore. And I can assure you, that is a long flight, especially when you have to stand the whole way.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.springfieldspringfield.co.uk/view_episode_scripts.php?tv-show=the-larry-sanders-show-1992&episode=s03e09|title=The Larry Sanders Show (1992) s03e09 Episode Script &#124; SS|website=Springfield! Springfield!}}</ref>\n\n[[Dr. Dre]] and [[Ice Cube]] referenced the caning in their 1994 single, \"[[Natural Born Killaz]]\".<ref>https://genius.com/Dr-dre-and-ice-cube-natural-born-killaz-lyrics Natural Born Killaz lyrics</ref>\n\nThe case inspired a 1995 ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode, \"[[Bart vs. Australia]]\", in which [[Australia]] is to punish Bart via \"booting\"\u2014a kick in the buttocks using a giant boot (later reduced to a shoe).<ref name=Mirkin>{{cite video |people=Mirkin, David |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 6 DVD commentary for the episode \"Bart vs. Australia\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Amos Yee]]\n*[[Judicial corporal punishment]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Latif, Asad (1994). ''The Flogging of Singapore: The Michael Fay Affair''. Singapore: Times Books International. {{ISBN|981-204-530-9}}\n*[[Gopal Baratham|Baratham, Gopal]] (1994). ''The Caning of Michael Fay''. Singapore: KRP Publication. {{ISBN|981-00-5747-4}}\n*Reyes, Alejandro (May 25, 1994). [http://www.corpun.com/awfay9405.htm Rough Justice: A Caning in Singapore Stirs Up a Fierce Debate About Crime And Punishment], ''Asiaweek'', Hong Kong.\n*The Asiaweek Newsmap (April 27, 1994). ''Asiaweek''.\n*Chew, Valerie (August 5, 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20090825175717/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1554_2009-08-06.html \"Michael Fay\"], ''Singapore Infopedia''. National Library Board.\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100920031803/http://corpun.com/sgju9404.htm#regrettable#regrettable The Singapore Government's response to the American Embassy's statement], April 1, 1994\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fay, Michael P.}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Caning in Singapore]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:People with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]]\n", "name_user": "Alarics", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic reaction:Fix refs.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_P._Fay"}
