{"title_page": "Marc Hodosh", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|image         = Marc hodosh hosting tedmed 2011.jpeg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Marc Hodosh hosting TEDMED conference 2011 in San Diego, CA.\n|birth_name    = Marc Hodosh\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|12|25}}\n|residence     = [[Brookline, Massachusetts]] and [[Santa Monica, California]]<ref name=\"xconomy\">{{cite news|title=Xconomy|url=http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/08/23/entrepreneur-segways-toward-medical-revolution-directing-genomics-x-prize/}}</ref>\n| alma_mater  = [[Ithaca College]], [[Boston University]]\n|nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n}}\n\n'''Marc Hodosh''' (born December 25, 1972) is an American entrepreneur who formerly owned, co-created and hosted the [[TEDMED|TEDMED conference]]. In September 2019, Marc Hodosh and [[Sanjay Gupta|Dr. Sanjay Gupta]] (CNN\u2019s Chief Medical Correspondent) announced a new event called Life Itself, set to launch in 2021 in partnership with CNN.\u00a0 Both Gupta and Hodosh will serve as hosts and organizers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lifeitself.health/|title=Life Itself with Dr. Sanjay Gupta and Marc Hodosh|website=Life Itself with Dr. Sanjay Gupta and Marc Hodosh|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\nHodosh previously led the Archon Genomics [[X PRIZE]], which followed the Ansari Space X PRIZE.  He has been a consultant to inventor [[Dean Kamen]] at DEKA Research & Development and also chaired Kamen's [[FIRST Robotics]] competition within the Boston region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston FIRST|url=http://www.bostonfirst.org}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, Hodosh founded and sold ID One, which specialized in facial recognition technology for the US Military and Intelligence communities.  He also led business development at Viisage, a previously publicly traded, facial recognition company.  Hodosh's first business and entrepreneurial endeavors began by inventing and importing a variety of consumer products from Asia, with distribution through Bed Bath & Beyond, QVC television, Toys-R-Us, and others.<ref>{{cite web|title=TEDMED|url=http://www.tedmed.com/about-tedmed/leadership-team}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hodosh Facebook page|url=http://www.facebook.com/hodosh/info}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHodosh graduated from [[Ithaca College]] in Ithaca, NY.  He moved to Boston in 1995 for [[Boston University School of Medicine|Boston University Medical School]] but after a year, he instead decided to focus on inventing & patenting consumer products.<ref>{{cite web|title=Xconomy|url=http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/08/23/entrepreneur-segways-toward-medical-revolution-directing-genomics-x-prize/}}</ref>\n\n== TEDMED ==\nMarc Hodosh bought the rights to TEDMED in 2008 from [[TED (conference)|TED]] creator Richard Saul Wurman, although the TEDMED event had not taken place for many years. In 2009, Hodosh re-launched TEDMED at the Hotel del Coronado in San Diego, California where it was held for the next three years and where Hodosh served as Host.<ref>{{cite web|title=TED|url=http://blog.ted.com/2010/01/19/tedmed_a_new_pa/}}</ref>   Wurman co-hosted the event with Hodosh for the first two years. In 2011, Hodosh sold TEDMED to Priceline founder, Jay Walker, who later moved the event to The Kennedy Center in Washington, DC in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=TEDMED|url=http://www.tedmed.com/home}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodosh, Marc}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Boston]]\n[[Category:Ithaca College alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:People from Brookline, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from California]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Marc Hodosh|timestamp=20200331173241|year=2020|month=March|day=31|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Marc Hodosh|date=31 March 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox person\n|image         = Marc hodosh hosting tedmed 2011.jpeg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Marc Hodosh hosting TEDMED conference 2011 in San Diego, CA.\n|birth_name    = Marc Hodosh\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|12|25}}\n|residence     = [[Brookline, Massachusetts]] and [[Santa Monica, California]]<ref name=\"xconomy\">{{cite news|title=Xconomy|url=http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/08/23/entrepreneur-segways-toward-medical-revolution-directing-genomics-x-prize/}}</ref>\n| alma_mater  = [[Ithaca College]], [[Boston University]]\n|nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n}}\n\n'''Marc Hodosh''' (born December 25, 1972) is an American entrepreneur who formerly owned, co-created and hosted the [[TEDMED|TEDMED conference]]. In September 2019, Marc Hodosh and [[Sanjay Gupta|Dr. Sanjay Gupta]] (CNN\u2019s Chief Medical Correspondent) announced a new event called Life Itself, set to launch in 2021 in partnership with CNN.\u00a0 Both Gupta and Hodosh will serve as hosts and organizers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lifeitself.health/|title=Life Itself with Dr. Sanjay Gupta and Marc Hodosh|website=Life Itself with Dr. Sanjay Gupta and Marc Hodosh|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\nHodosh previously led the Archon Genomics [[X PRIZE]], which followed the Ansari Space X PRIZE.  He has been a consultant to inventor [[Dean Kamen]] at DEKA Research & Development and also chaired Kamen's [[FIRST Robotics]] competition within the Boston region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston FIRST|url=http://www.bostonfirst.org}}</ref>\n\nEarlier, Hodosh founded and sold ID One, which specialized in facial recognition technology for the US Military and Intelligence communities.  He also led business development at Viisage, a previously publicly traded, facial recognition company.  Hodosh's first business and entrepreneurial endeavors began by inventing and importing a variety of consumer products from Asia, with distribution through Bed Bath & Beyond, QVC television, Toys-R-Us, and others.<ref>{{cite web|title=TEDMED|url=http://www.tedmed.com/about-tedmed/leadership-team}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hodosh Facebook page|url=http://www.facebook.com/hodosh/info}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nHodosh graduated from [[Ithaca College]] in Ithaca, NY.  He moved to Boston in 1995 for [[Boston University School of Medicine|Boston University Medical School]] but after a year, he instead decided to focus on inventing & patenting consumer products.<ref>{{cite web|title=Xconomy|url=http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2007/08/23/entrepreneur-segways-toward-medical-revolution-directing-genomics-x-prize/}}</ref>\n\n== TEDMED ==\nMarc Hodosh bought the rights to TEDMED in 2008 from [[TED (conference)|TED]] creator Richard Saul Wurman, although the TEDMED event had not taken place for many years. In 2009, Hodosh re-launched TEDMED at the Hotel del Coronado in San Diego, California where it was held for the next three years and where Hodosh served as Host.<ref>{{cite web|title=TED|url=http://blog.ted.com/2010/01/19/tedmed_a_new_pa/}}</ref>   Wurman co-hosted the event with Hodosh for the first two years. In 2011, Hodosh sold TEDMED to Priceline founder, Jay Walker, who later moved the event to The Kennedy Center in Washington, DC in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=TEDMED|url=http://www.tedmed.com/home}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hodosh, Marc}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Boston]]\n[[Category:Ithaca College alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:People from Brookline, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from California]]\n", "name_user": "73.78.158.214", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marc_Hodosh"}
{"title_page": "List of movie umbrella titles in North America", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Lists|date=August 2010}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2013}}\n}}\nThis is a '''listing of topics pertaining to [[movies]] broadcast on [[television]] under various [[umbrella title]]s'''.  Unless otherwise noted, all titles are presented based upon the chronological order or time of day in which they were first broadcast.<ref name=\"Brooks\">Tim Brooks and Earle Marsh, ''The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows: 1946-Present'' New York: Ballantine Books, 1979, 1981, 1985, 1988, 1992, 1995, 1999, 2003. {{ISBN|0-345-45542-8}}</ref>\n\n==Movie umbrella titles on [[network television]]==\n\n===[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''ABC Feature Film'' (1948\u20131949, Thursday; 1949, Thursday-Friday; 1950\u20131951, Monday)\n* ''Film Shorts'' (1950\u20131951, Sunday)\n* ''First Nighter'' (1950\u20131951, Wednesday)\n* ''Admission Free'' (May\u2013August 1951, Monday; August\u2013December 1951, Sunday)\n* ''Comedy Parade'' (1951, Monday)\n* ''Curtain Up'' (May\u2013September 1951, Tuesday; October\u2013December 1951, Monday/Saturday)\n* ''Hollywood Adventure Time'' (1951, Sunday)\n* ''Hollywood Movie Time'' (1951, Wednesday; 1952, Saturday)\n* ''Hollywood Mystery Time'' (1951, Tuesday)\n* ''King's Crossroads'' (1951, Wednesday; 1951\u20131952, Sunday)\n* ''Northwest Patrol'' (1951, Wednesday)\n* ''Saddle Pal Club'' (1951\u20131952, Saturday)\n* ''Screen Shorts'' (1951, Sunday)\n* ''Cinema-Scope'' (1952, Sunday)\n* ''Encore Playhouse'' (1952, Friday)\n* ''Feature Playhouse'' (1952\u20131953, Saturday)\n* ''Washday Theatre'' (1952, Monday)\n* ''[[Walt Disney anthology television series|Walt Disney's Disneyland]]'' (1954\u20131958)<ref name=\"eotv\">{{cite web|last1=Griffin|first1=Sean|title=Walt Disney Programs|url=http://www.museum.tv/eotv/waltdisneyp.htm|website=Encyclopedia of Television|publisher=[[Museum of Broadcast Communications]]|accessdate=March 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817202754/http://www.museum.tv/eotv/waltdisneyp.htm|archive-date=August 17, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n**''Walt Disney Presents'' (1958\u20131961)<ref name=\"eotv\"/>\n**''The Disney Sunday Movie'' (1986\u20131988)<ref name=\"eotv\"/><ref name=drn>{{cite news |last=Pierce |first=Scott |date=September 28, 1997 |title=ABC revives weekly Disney series |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/585719/ABC-revives-weekly-Disney-series.html | work=Deseret News |location= |access-date=March 14, 2016 }}</ref>\n** ''[[The Wonderful World of Disney]] (1997\u2013<ref name=drn/> 2008)\n* ''[[Famous Film Festival]]'' (1955\u20131956, Sunday; 1956\u20131957, Saturday)\n* ''[[Afternoon Film Festival]]'' (1956-1957, Monday-Friday)\n* ''Film Fair'' (1956, Monday)\n* ''Hour Glass'' (1956, Thursday)\n* ''Hollywood Film Theater'' (1957, Sunday)\n* ''[[The ABC Sunday Night Movie]]'' (1962\u20131963, 1964\u20131998)\n* ''The ABC Wednesday Night Movie'' (1967\u20131970)\n* ''The ABC Monday Night Movie'' (1971\u20131998)\n* ''The Movies of David O. Selznick'' (1971\u20131972)\n* ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]'' (1989-1994,<ref name=eot-HHoF>{{cite book|last1=Shapiro|first1=Mitchell|title=Encyclopedia of Television|publisher=[[Museum of Broadcast Communications]]|url=http://www.museum.tv/eotv/hallmarkhall.htm|accessdate=January 3, 2018|chapter=Hallmark Hall of Fame}}</ref> 2011-2014) from CBS both times, return to CBS in 1994\n* ''The ABC Big Picture Show'' (1998\u20132002)\n* ''The ABC Sunday Picture Show'' (1998\u20132002)\n* ''ABC Saturday Night at the Movies'' (2002\u20132003)\n* ''ABC Saturday Movie of the Week  '' (2003\u2013present)\n* ''[[ABC Movie of the Week|The Movie of the Week]]'' (1969\u20131981)\n* ''The Movie of the Weekend'' (1971\u20131972)\n* ''The Saturday Superstar Movie'' (1972\u20131974)\n* ''ABC Suspense Movie'' (1973\u20131974)\n* ''[[ABC Theater]]'' (c. 1974\u20131995)\n* ''The ABC Mystery Movie'' (1989, Monday; 1989\u20131990, Saturday)\n* ''The ABC Family Movie'' (1993\u20131998)\n* ''The ABC Kids Movie Matinee'' (1994\u20132002)\n* ''ABC Premiere Event'' (1998\u20132005)\n{{colend}}\n\n===[[CBS]]===\n* ''Film Theatre of the Air'' (1949, Saturday; 1951 and 1953, Tuesday)\n* ''Premiere Playhouse'' (March\u2013July 1949, Friday; 1949\u20131950, Saturday)\n* ''Budweiser Summer Theatre'' (1951, Saturday)\n* ''Schlitz Film Firsts'' (1951, Friday)\n* ''Summer Cinema'' (1952, Saturday)\n* ''[[CBS Thursday Night Movie|The CBS Thursday Night Movies]]'' (1965\u20131976)\n* ''The CBS Friday Night Movies'' (1966\u20131977)\n* ''The CBS Children's Film Festival'' (1967-1984)\n* ''The New CBS Tuesday Night Movies'' (1972\u20131974)\n* ''The CBS Wednesday Night Movies'' (1977\u20131981)\n* ''The CBS Tuesday Night Movies'' (1978\u20131986)\n* ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]'' (1979 to 1981, 1981-1989, 1994-2011) from NBC, and back to CBS then to ABC twice<ref name=eot-HHoF/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title='Hallmark Hall Of Fame' Ends On CBS|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/05/hallmark-hall-of-fame-ends-on-cbs/|accessdate=January 3, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 6, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''The CBS Saturday Night Movies'' (1981\u20131986)\n* ''CBS Sunday Movie'' (1986\u20132006)\n* ''CBS Tuesday Movie'' (1986\u20131999)\n* ''CBS Wednesday Movie'' (1999\u20132001)\n* ''[[CBS Late Movie|The CBS Late Movie]]'' (1972\u20131989)\n* ''A CBS Special Movie Presentation'' (1974\u2013present)\n\n===[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]===\n* ''Fox Night at the Movies'' (1990\u20131998)\n* ''[[Family Movie Night]]'' (2011) films aired under a [[brokered programming|time brokerage]] agreement with [[Walmart]] and [[Procter & Gamble]], moved over from NBC for 2 films<ref name=\"dl1\">{{cite news|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Procter & Gamble Producing 2-Hour Family Friendly Movie To Air On Fox As Time Buy|url=http://deadline.com/2010/12/procter-gamble-producing-2-hour-movie-backdoor-pilot-to-air-on-fox-as-time-buy-87638/|accessdate=February 27, 2018|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=December 2, 2010}}</ref> then back\n* ''Fox Presents'' (2015-present)\n\n===[[NBC]]===\n* ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]'' (1951-1979)<ref name=eot-HHoF/>\n*World Premiere Movies (11/1966\u20131967) 8 [[Television film]]s<ref name=ABCMOW>Michael McKenna. (August 22, 2013). Page xix. [https://books.google.com/books?id=IVCFAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=ABC+Circle+Films&source=bl&ots=WKTIMLSvBK&sig=tBslJiZ7LNP5fkg9JOE8Qn3VFSQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6ODCUoW1KoXqkQfI84DYBw&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=ABC%20Circle%20Films&f=false The ABC Movie of the Week: Big Movies for the Small Screen]. Scarecrow Press. Accessed on December 31, 2013.</ref>\n* ''NBC Sunday Night at the Movies'' (1981\u20131990)\n* ''NBC Sunday Night Movie'' (1990\u20132001)\n* ''The Sunday Big Event'' (1979\u20131981)\n* ''NBC Monday Night Movie'' (1990\u20131997)\n* ''[[The NBC Monday Movie|NBC Monday Night at the Movies]]'' (1963\u20131964, 1968\u20131990)\n* ''NBC Tuesday Night at the Movies'' (1965\u20131971)\n* ''NBC Wednesday Night at the Movies'' (1964\u20131965)\n* ''[[NBC Saturday Night at the Movies]]'' (1961\u20131978)\n* ''NBC Saturday Night Movie'' (2000 \u2013 mid-2002)\n* ''[[NBC Mystery Movie|The NBC Mystery Movie]]'' (1971\u20131977)\n* ''The NBC Big Event'' (1976\u20131979)\n* ''[[Family Movie Night]]'' (2010\u20132011) films aired under a [[brokered programming|time brokerage]] agreement with [[Walmart]] and [[Procter & Gamble]], with two appearing on Fox<ref name=\"dl1\"/>\n\n==Nationally syndicated movie umbrella titles and anthology series==\n* ''Embassy Night at the Movies'' (1983-1988)\n* ''Columbia Showcase'' (1980s)\n* ''New World Showcase'' (1980s\u20131990s)\n* ''[[Fourth television network#MGM Family Network|The MGM Family Network]]'' (1973-1976) also considered an \"occasional\" television network\n* ''[[SFM Holiday Network]]'' (1978\u20131992)  also considered an \"occasional\" television network\n* ''[[Fourth television network#Premiere Network|MGM/UA Premiere Network]]'' (1984-1991)  also considered an ad hoc television network\n* ''[[Fourth television network#Debut Network|Universal Pictures Debut Network]]'' (1985\u20131990) also considered an ad hoc television network\n* ''Universal Theatre'' (1991\u20131994)\n* ''Columbia Night at the Movies'' (late 1980s\u20131990s)\n* ''TriStar Showcase'' (1988\u20131994)\n* ''The Orbis Showcase Network'' (1980s)\n* ''TV Net'' (1980s)\n* ''The Movie Greats Network'' (1980s \u2013 early 1990s)\n* ''The Best Picture Show'' (mid-1990s)\n* ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' (1990s)\n* ''The Heritage Movie Network'' (1990s \u2013 late 2000s)\n* ''[[Midnight Monster Hop]] (2006\u20132009)\n* ''[[Wolfman Mac's Chiller Drive-In]]'' (2008-2011)\n* ''Tonight Only'' (late 1980s \u2013 1990s)\n* ''Columbia Showcase Theater'' (2000\u2013present)\n* ''MGM Showcase'' (2009\u20132011)\n* ''[[Elvira's Movie Macabre]]'' (2010\u20132011)\n* ''MGM Showcase Theater'' (2012\u2013present)\n\n==Movie umbrella titles on [[Pay television|cable and satellite television]]==\n\n*''[[Animal Planet]] at the Movies'' (May 19, 2007-<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dempsey|first1=John|title=Animal Planet slates movie night|url=https://variety.com/2007/scene/markets-festivals/animal-planet-slates-movie-night-1117962461/|accessdate=March 2, 2018|work=Variety|date=April 4, 2007}}</ref>)\n* ''[[DVD on TV]]'' () [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]\n* ''Movies That Don't Suck'' (2008\u20132012) [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]]\n* [[Syfy]] Saturday Original Movie\n* ''Movies That Rock'' - [[VH1]]\n* ''Rock & Roll Picture Show'' [[VH1 Classic]]\n* ''Flick and a Forecast'' (Friday nights; 2010) [[The Weather Channel]]\n\n===[[Cartoon Network]]===\n* ''Mr. Spim's Cartoon Theater'' (1995\u20131998)\n* ''Cartoon Theater'' (1998\u20132007)\n* ''Movie M