{"title_page": "John Cohn", "text_new": "{{short description|American engineer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = Dr\n| name   = John Cohn\n| image     = Jcrainbow.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption  = John Cohn giving a talk at [[TEDx Delft]] in 2013.\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1959|02|09|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation     = IBM Fellow and Computer Engineer\n| spouse         = Diane Mariano<ref>[http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/top-ten/john-cohn.html \"The Colony: John Cohn's Top Tens List\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130052039/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/top-ten/john-cohn.html |date=2012-01-30 }}, which references his wife by name.</ref>\n| children       = Max, Sam (Died 2006), Gabe\n}}\n'''John Maxwell Cohn''' (born February 9, 1959) is an American engineer.  Cohn is best known as the engineer scientist in the [[Discovery Channel]] TV show, [[The Colony (U.S. TV series)|The Colony]].<ref name=\"vermontpaper\">{{cite web |last1=James |first1=Megan |title=Engineering Evangelist |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/vermont/engineering-evangelist/Content?oid=2144716 |website=Seven Days |publisher=Da Capo Publishing |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> He is an [[IBM Fellow]] in at the MIT-IBM Watson AI Laboratory. Previous to that John was Chief Scientist of the  [[Internet of Things]] division.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Brief Bio|url=http://johncohn.org/base/about/bio/#sthash.LY823JUe.cV8z7hmf.dpbs|website=johncohn.org|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> He holds an undergraduate electrical engineering degree from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], as well as a doctoral degree from [[Carnegie Mellon University]]. Cohn has authored over 40 papers and has more than 120 worldwide patents.<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=John Cohn IBM Fellow|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/john-cohn|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCohn's presentation concerning electricity, entitled ''Jolts and Volts'', has been performed for more than 50,000 students world wide, including performances at [[Walt Disney World]], and the [[New York Hall of Science]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John Cohn The Computer Engineer|url=http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/bios/john-cohn.html|website=dsc.discovery.com|accessdate=1 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416042130/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/bios/john-cohn.html|archivedate=April 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Cohn: ECE Alumnus, IBM Fellow & Role Model|url=http://www.ece.cmu.edu/news/story/2007/08/john_cohn_ece.html|website=Electrical and Computer Engineering|accessdate=1 November 2017|date=August 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 Cohn was a presenter at a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx]] conference. TEDxDelft 2013 was themed \"Do try this at home\" and Cohn's talk was titled \"The importance of play\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.tedxdelft.nl/tedxdelfts2013/|title = TEDxDelft 2013|date = 4 October 2013|accessdate = July 17, 2014|website = TEDxDelft 2013|publisher = TEDx|last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://tedxtalks.ted.com/video/The-importance-of-play-John-Coh|title = The importance of play: John Cohn at TEDxDelft|date = December 19, 2013|accessdate = July 17, 2014|website = Watch \"The importance of play: John Cohn at TEDxDelft\" Video at TEDxTalks|publisher = TEDx|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131002063819/https://www.cuspconference.com/videos.php?videos.php%3Fsection=John-Cohn#videos.php?section=John-Cohn Presenting at Cusp Conference 2009 (video)]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohn, John Maxwell}}\n[[Category:IBM Fellows]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n\n\n{{US-engineer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American engineer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name   = John Cohn\n| image     = John Cohn (20178592395).jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption  = John Cohn giving a talk in 2015 at [[Campus Party]] in [[Mexico]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1959|02|09|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation     = IBM Fellow and Computer Engineer\n| spouse         = Diane Mariano<ref>[http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/top-ten/john-cohn.html \"The Colony: John Cohn's Top Tens List\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130052039/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/top-ten/john-cohn.html |date=2012-01-30 }}, which references his wife by name.</ref>\n| children       = Max, Sam (Died 2006), Gabe\n}}\n'''John Maxwell Cohn''' (born February 9, 1959) is an American engineer.  Cohn is best known as the engineer scientist in the [[Discovery Channel]] TV show, [[The Colony (U.S. TV series)|The Colony]].<ref name=\"vermontpaper\">{{cite web |last1=James |first1=Megan |title=Engineering Evangelist |url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/vermont/engineering-evangelist/Content?oid=2144716 |website=Seven Days |publisher=Da Capo Publishing |accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> He is an [[IBM Fellow]] in at the MIT-IBM Watson AI Laboratory. Previous to that John was Chief Scientist of the  [[Internet of Things]] division.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Brief Bio|url=http://johncohn.org/base/about/bio/#sthash.LY823JUe.cV8z7hmf.dpbs|website=johncohn.org|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> He holds an undergraduate electrical engineering degree from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], as well as a doctoral degree from [[Carnegie Mellon University]]. Cohn has authored over 40 papers and has more than 120 worldwide patents.<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=John Cohn IBM Fellow|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/john-cohn|website=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nCohn's presentation concerning electricity, entitled ''Jolts and Volts'', has been performed for more than 50,000 students world wide, including performances at [[Walt Disney World]], and the [[New York Hall of Science]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John Cohn The Computer Engineer|url=http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/bios/john-cohn.html|website=dsc.discovery.com|accessdate=1 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416042130/http://dsc.discovery.com/tv/colony/bios/john-cohn.html|archivedate=April 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Cohn: ECE Alumnus, IBM Fellow & Role Model|url=http://www.ece.cmu.edu/news/story/2007/08/john_cohn_ece.html|website=Electrical and Computer Engineering|accessdate=1 November 2017|date=August 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 Cohn was a presenter at a [[TED (conference)#TEDx|TEDx]] conference. TEDxDelft 2013 was themed \"Do try this at home\" and Cohn's talk was titled \"The importance of play\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.tedxdelft.nl/tedxdelfts2013/|title = TEDxDelft 2013|date = 4 October 2013|accessdate = July 17, 2014|website = TEDxDelft 2013|publisher = TEDx|last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://tedxtalks.ted.com/video/The-importance-of-play-John-Coh|title = The importance of play: John Cohn at TEDxDelft|date = December 19, 2013|accessdate = July 17, 2014|website = Watch \"The importance of play: John Cohn at TEDxDelft\" Video at TEDxTalks|publisher = TEDx|last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131002063819/https://www.cuspconference.com/videos.php?videos.php%3Fsection=John-Cohn#videos.php?section=John-Cohn Presenting at Cusp Conference 2009 (video)]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohn, John Maxwell}}\n[[Category:IBM Fellows]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n\n\n{{US-